- Fri 26 Jul 2019
Helen Branswell https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell [edited]
1. It seems the daily update newsletter out of DRC is being revived. Here's some info from Fri [26 Jul 2019], I think.
+11 cases, looks like 12 deaths (4 confirmed, 8 in the community. Outbreak totals: 2641 cases, 1773 deaths.

2. The report that came out overnight (currently available thru WhatsApp only) catches up a bit on the days last week for which there was no update. This shows the number of people released from treatment centers (CTE) having been cured:
19, Beni; 9 Mabalako; 6, Katwa; 1 Butembo

3. Big jump yesterday (27 Jul 2019): +18 cases. That's the highest single day increase in July 2019, though one other day (19 Jul 2019) also recorded 18 cases.

4. Most of these 18 #Ebola cases are from Beni (11). I believe 3/18 are health workers. If yes, that would bring health worker infections to 145. But there's been a fair amount of discrepancy lately with different places listing different HCW numbers, so not sure.

5. Of the 18 #Ebola cases confirmed Sat [27 Jul 2019], 7 were children under the age of 18. Actually, all are 9 & under. Five remain alive; 2 have died; 6 weren't vaccinated; no info on #7.

- Fri 26 Jul 2019. South Sudan: not a case
[Middle East Monitor, abridged, edited]
https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20190726-south-sudan-no-confirmed-ebola-case/

Ebola virus. Suspected case in South Sudan earlier this week has NOT been confirmed.
------------------
South Sudan is free from Ebola after reports of a suspected case early this week, which has caused panic among citizens of the African country, the deputy information minister said Friday [26 Jul 2019], Anadolu reported.

"Health Minister Dr Riek Gai Kok has announced in today's [26 Jul 2019] cabinet meeting that there is no Ebola case in South Sudan so citizens should not panic," Lily Albino Akol said.

"There is no confirmed Ebola case in the country. Early this week there was a scare whereby a patient [40-year-old woman] has shown symptoms related to Ebola, including bleeding, and people thought that it might be Ebola," she said.

"However, the preliminary results from the laboratory tests on the Ebola case in Juba have proven that the patient does not have the virus," Akol told journalists after the cabinet meeting.

According to Dr. Riek Gai, more samples have been sent to Uganda for further verification.

